Date: Tue, 11 Dec 2001 22:50:51 +0100
From: Tomas Jelinek <jelinek@lrz.uni-muenchen.de>

ProMED-mail readers may be interested in this message, which has been
discussed
within TropNetEurop today.
At our outpatient department we have recently seen a following
patient:
Male, 29y, German national, travelled for 20 days in Thailand (whole
country including jungle areas in the North), return on 15 Nov 2001,
first symptoms on 17 Nov 2001: fever (up to 39.9 degrees C, massive
headache and myalgia). First presentation on 20 Nov. 2001.Clinical
examination was normal, malaria smear repeatedly negative, moderate
leukocytosis, CRP, creatinine and liver enzymes elevated,
macrohematuria. Ultrasound of abdomen showed splenomegaly. Serological
tests for leptospirosis were initially negative but became highly
positive during further clinical course. Full recovery under
[treatment with ciprofloxacine plus ampicillin.
The patient did no rafting, nor did he swim in fresh water, [but he
hiked in jungle areas of North Thailand and did some wading in rivers
there.
--
Ole Wichmann & Tomas Jelinek
Tomas Jelinek, MD
TropNetEurop coordinator
University of Munich
Department of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine
Leopoldstr. 5, 80802 Munich, Germany
